      "end": 17.14,
      "text": "Recorded by Kim Stone of Pirling on the Dark Side in Denver, Colorado, USA.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 18.34,
      "end": 20.88,
      "text": "ESOP's Fables, The Boy and the Snails.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-005",
      "start": 21.64,
      "end": 26.62,
      "text": "A farmer's boy went looking for snails, and when he had picked up both his hands full,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-006",
      "start": 26.62,
      "end": 31.76,
      "text": "he said about making a fire at which to roast them, for he meant to eat them.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-007",
      "start": 32.48,
      "end": 37.0,
      "text": "When it got well alight and the snails began to fill the heat, they gradually",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-008",
      "start": 37.0,
      "end": 42.12,
      "text": "withdrew more and more into their shells with the hissing noise they always make",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-009",
      "start": 42.12,
      "end": 42.92,
      "text": "when they do so.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-010",
      "start": 43.64,
      "end": 46.78,
      "text": "When the boy heard it, he said, you abandon creatures.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-011",
      "start": 47.78,
      "end": 50.88,
      "text": "How can you find heart to whistle when your houses are burning?",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-012",
      "start": 51.84,
      "end": 54.02,
      "text": "End of The Boy and the Snails.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
